<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bill has always had a thing for Warren Buffett,=
 as my faithful
readers know. In fact, he seems to believe the current deal, if completed, =
would give him a leg up on his idol. As Bill recently <a href=3D"https://em=
ail.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWUk5EUmgxUk9MN=
zIxZHpScDZoUT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tdGhlLW9y=
YWNlLW9mLWJyby1tYWhhLz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyU=
yODIlMkYyNiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRV=
JTKyUyODIlMkYyNiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwi=
aW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMDQ1NTU5fQ/546e1d28=
851e7ce3f8d0e64626acdaf629e167596d945342a51e68835998eada" style=3D"text-dec=
oration:underline;color:#d40000;">told me</a>, Howard Hughes is =E2=80=9Ca =
lot better than a crappy textile company, right? It=E2=80=99s actually a re=
ally good business. And it=E2=80=99s going to become a lot more cash-flow p=
ositive over the next decade, and we can just redeploy that capital.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bill has tried any number of tactics over the=
 years to obtain his version of =E2=80=9Cpermanent capital,=E2=80=9D includ=
ing the largest SPAC ever=E2=80=94which later got completely unwound=E2=80=
=94and something Bill called a =E2=80=9CSPARC,=E2=80=9D which is still floa=
ting around out there, waiting for a company to buy. His motivation for fut=
zing with Howard Hughes, he explained on the Spaces chat, was the fact that=
 it=E2=80=99s essentially been a dud of an
investment since it was spun off from General Growth Properties, one of Bil=
l=E2=80=99s huge winners back in the day. Bill noted that he=E2=80=99s been=
 on the Howard Hughes board since it was spun off and that, in 2019, the co=
mpany hired Centerview Partners to do =E2=80=9Ca full-court press=E2=80=9D =
and sell the company. Alas, there were no takers.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>Last summer, he hired Jefferies to take Howard Hughes private. The bank ap=
proached
284 investors, 40 of which signed nondisclosure agreements and kicked the t=
ires. Around 20 of the 40 took the next step. But, in the end, there were n=
o =E2=80=9Cformal=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cinformal=E2=80=9D expressions of int=
erest in the company. Another goose egg. (Potential investors couldn=E2=80=
=99t see the =E2=80=9Cpath to liquidity=E2=80=9D after taking the company p=
rivate, Bill said.)=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Bill Ackman,=
 man of action, had to do <em>something</em>. On a trip to the beach over C=
hristmas, he realized the answer
was right there in front of him, like a beached whale: Turn Howard Hughes i=
nto <em>his</em> Berkshire Hathaway!</p></div>
