:
28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The White Whale</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:22px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">During his livestream last week, Bill said the =
special committee of
the Howard Hughes board had only two questions to answer. First: Should Bil=
l and Pershing be allowed to increase their stake to 48 percent? He thinks =
this should be an easy one, since the transaction wouldn=E2=80=99t result i=
n a change of control. =E2=80=9CAt 37.6 percent, we=E2=80=99re already obvi=
ously a very influential shareholder in the company,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=
=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think our influence meaningfully changes=E2=80=9D whe=
n Pershing increases that stake to 48 percent. The second question is more =
complicated: Does Howard Hughes,
itself, want to become the next Berkshire Hathaway? If so, should Pershing =
Square be paid for its help in transforming the company, and what form shou=
ld that compensation take?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bill tried to answer t=
hese questions with a long-winded stem-winder about Pershing Square=E2=80=
=99s stellar track record=E2=80=94a few clunkers aside, such as Valeant Pha=
rmaceuticals, Herbalife, and JCPenney=E2=80=94and how much value he and his=
 team
can bring to the table on behalf of Howard Hughes=E2=80=99 shareholders. =
=E2=80=9CWhat is happening here is a new management team that=E2=80=99s com=
ing on board to run the holding company, and we=E2=80=99re adding an extra =
$810 million to our investment in a company=E2=80=94a personal investment,=
=E2=80=9D Bill said. =E2=80=9CThis has to be the largest investment probabl=
y ever made by a new management team stepping in to run a public company.=
=E2=80=9D He told listeners that his personal investment in the company wou=
ld increase to $764 million; the only other
personal investment he has of that magnitude is what he has in Pershing Squ=
are Holdings, his publicly traded investment company based in Amsterdam.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As for the fees he=E2=80=99s charging, Bill argued =
that Howard Hughes would be getting a <em>bargain</em>. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=
=99re getting paid one and a half percent in this transaction of the equity=
 market cap of Howard Hughes going forward, paid on a quarterly basis,=E2=
=80=9D he said.
=E2=80=9CNo promotes, no performance allocation, no performance-based fees,=
 no equity, no options, no restricted stock.=E2=80=9D He said he normally c=
harges fees of 1.5 percent of assets under management <em>plus</em> a =E2=
=80=9Cperformance=E2=80=9D fee of between 16 percent and 20 percent based o=
n realized and unrealized gains. So, you know, a bargain for Howard Hughes.=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">On the Spaces call, Bill also took questions from some=
 of the 2,000
or so people listening in. I asked Bill how his revised offer to invest $90=
0 million in Howard Hughes advanced his goal of being his generation=E2=80=
=99s Buffett. (I couldn=E2=80=99t resist.) You=E2=80=99ll be stunned to hea=
r that he wasn=E2=80=99t modest: =E2=80=9CBuffett was an inspiration to me =
when I was in my early 20s, =E2=80=A6 and he=E2=80=99s been an inspiration =
ever since,=E2=80=9D Bill said, adding that when he raised <em>his</em> fir=
st hedge fund, at age 26, he resolved to have a =E2=80=9C<em>better</em> re=
cord=E2=80=9D than Warren. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s good to set a high
bar.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">What makes Buffett unique, of cours=
e, is that he truly has <em>permanent capital</em>=E2=80=94investors can=E2=
=80=99t take their money away from him if they get nervous for whatever rea=
son. They could always sell their Berkshire Hathaway stock, but that doesn=
=E2=80=99t remove money from Warren=E2=80=99s cash hoard, as would happen i=
f, say, a limited partner wanted their money back from Bill=E2=80=99s hedge=
 fund. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s much harder to
manage capital when your money can disappear overnight,=E2=80=9D Bill said =
on the call. Bill does have a permanent capital vehicle of sorts in Pershin=
g Square Holdings, which buys minority stakes in public companies. But he w=
ants more flexibility. =E2=80=9CThe big advantage Buffett has beyond perman=
ent capital is he owns businesses that generate cash and generate excess ca=
sh that he can redeploy into buying new businesses,=E2=80=9D Bill said in a=
nswer to my question. =E2=80=9CThe holy grail is to have a public entity=E2=
=80=94permanent
capital=E2=80=94that owns operating businesses that generate more cash than=
 they can use in their <em>own</em> business, that you can redeploy in buyi=
ng new companies.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bill went on to reiterate t=
hat his revised proposal puts $900 million more cash on Howard Hughes=E2=80=
=99s balance sheet, and that capital, along with the existing $500 million,=
 gives the company $1.4 billion of firepower for acquiring companies. Over
time, he said, the deal will provide him and Howard Hughes shareholders a n=
ice return. =E2=80=9CAnd that=E2=80=99s why it works,=E2=80=9D he concluded=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br=
/>Well, maybe. It=E2=80=99s still a mo=
dest amount of firepower for someone with Buffett-like ambitions. And since=
 Bill announced his $900 million purchase offer last week, Howard Hughes st=
ock has been a nothingburger, down about 9 percent. Bill has the ability to=
 make everything he does seem like a profound bit of alchemy, but it doesn=
=E2=80=99t always
work out that way. Which reminds me of something Bill told <em>me</em> that=
 Warren once told <em>him</em>: =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The only person who could=
 cause you more harm than a thief with a dagger is a journalist with a pen.=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Bill paused for a moment while conjuring the memory. =E2=
=80=9CThose were very powerful words.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
